\f1\fs32 Flanged joints are made by bolting together two adjacent flanges with a gasket between them to provide a seal.  Flanged connections are used for higher-pressure applications and situations where dismantling might be necessary. \
The materials and design of the flanges are governed by the requirements of service, and in most cases, a flange is of the same material as the pipe.  Flanges in steel piping systems are usually screwed or welded to the pipe or tubing, while flanges in nonferrous systems are usually brazed.\
A 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f3\b\fs32 blind flange
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  (also called a '
\f0\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f3\b\fs32 closure plate flange
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32 ') has no center hole, so nothing can flow through the flange. Blind flanges may be used to temporarily seal a piping system while testing, modifying or repairing the line, to create an access point in a piping system,  or to create a long-term seal to terminate a piping system that is not used.\
